\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(Q2)
\series default
: Consider the recursively defined sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}=1$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{n+1}=3-y_{n},
\]

\end_inset

and set 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\lim\,y_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(y_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(y_{n+1}\right)$
\end_inset

 have the same limit, taking the limit across the recursive equation gives
 
\begin_inset Formula $y=3-y$
\end_inset

.
 Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, we conclude 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim\,y_{n}=3/2$
\end_inset

.
 What is wrong with this argument?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(y_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,2,1,2,1,2,1,2,\cdots\right\} $
\end_inset

, and doesn't have a limit.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 cannot be the limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}$
\end_inset

 since the limit doesn't exist.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(Q3(a))
\series default
: Show that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{2},\sqrt{2+\sqrt{2}},\sqrt{2+\sqrt{2+\sqrt{2}}},\ldots
\]

\end_inset

converges and find the limit.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Consider the recursively defined sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n+1}=\sqrt{2+a_{n}}.
\]

\end_inset

We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a_{n}\right)\to2$
\end_inset

.
 We do this by first showing that the sequence has converges by showing
 that it has an upper bound and that sequence continually increases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
To show that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

 has an upper bound, we want to show that the open sentence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q\left(n\right):a_{n}<2
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\N$
\end_inset

.
 We work this by induction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Base Case
\series default
: We first verify 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a_{1} & =\sqrt{2}<2\\
a_{2} & =\sqrt{2+\sqrt{2}}<\sqrt{2+2}=2.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Induction Step
\series default
: We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 is true for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\N$
\end_inset

 and we want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\left(k+1\right)$
\end_inset

 is true.
 Well, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{k+1}=\sqrt{2+a_{k}},
\]

\end_inset

and since 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}<2$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a_{k+1} & <\sqrt{2+2}\\
 & =2,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

thus 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 is an upper bound of the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}<a_{2}<a_{3}<\cdots<a_{n}<a_{n+1}$
\end_inset

, the sequence is monotonically increasing.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

 is monotonic and bounded, the sequence converges.
 Thus a limit exists.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We now know that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

 converges.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a_{n}\right)=L$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lim\left(a_{n+1}\right) & =\sqrt{2+\lim\left(a_{n}\right)}\\
L & =\sqrt{2+L},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L^{2}-L-2=0.
\]

\end_inset

This gives 
\begin_inset Formula $L=-1,2$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L=2$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a_{n}\right)=2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(Q5(a))
\series default
: Calculating square roots.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=2$
\end_inset

, and define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{n+1}=\frac{1}{2}\left(x_{n}+\frac{2}{x_{n}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is always greater than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, and then use this to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}-x_{n+1}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim\,x_{n}=\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We will first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is always greater than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
We want to prove the open sentence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q\left(n\right):\,x_{n}^{2}\geq2
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=2$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n+1}=\frac{1}{2}\left(x_{n}+\frac{2}{x_{n}}\right)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x_{n+1}^{2} & =\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(x_{n}+\frac{2}{x_{n}}\right)\right)^{2}\\
 & =\frac{x_{n}^{2}}{4}+1+\frac{1}{x_{n}^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Base Case
\series default
: We first verify 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x_{1}^{2} & =4\geq2\\
x_{2}^{2} & =\frac{4}{4}+1+\frac{1}{4}=2.25\geq2.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Induction Step
\series default
: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\N$
\end_inset

.
 We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 is true, and we want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\left(k+1\right)$
\end_inset

 is true.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x_{k+1}^{2} & =\frac{x_{k}^{2}}{4}+1+\frac{1}{x_{k}^{2}}\\
 & \geq\frac{2}{4}+1+\frac{1}{2}\\
 & =2,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\left(n\right)$
\end_inset

 is true.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}-x_{n+1}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
We suppose directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n+1}=\frac{1}{2}\left(x_{n}+\frac{2}{x_{n}}\right)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x_{n}-x_{n+1} & =x_{n}-\frac{1}{2}\left(x_{n}+\frac{2}{x_{n}}\right)\\
 & =x_{n}-\frac{x_{n}}{2}-\frac{1}{x_{n}}\\
 & =\frac{x_{n}}{2}-\frac{1}{x_{n}}\\
 & =\frac{x_{n}^{2}-2}{2x_{n}},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}^{2}\geq2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\N$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{x_{n}^{2}-2}{2x_{n}}\geq0,
\]

\end_inset

which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}-x_{n+1}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim\,x_{n}=\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}-x_{n+1}\geq0$
\end_inset

, the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 is monotonically decreasing.
 Also, since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}^{2}\geq2$
\end_inset

, two serves as a lower bound.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\lim\,x_{n}=\lim\,x_{n+1}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lim\,x_{n+1} & =\lim\,\frac{1}{2}\left(x_{n}+\frac{2}{x_{n}}\right)\\
x & =\frac{1}{2}x+\frac{1}{x}\\
x^{2} & =\frac{1}{2}x^{2}+1\\
\frac{1}{2}x^{2} & =1\\
x & =\sqrt{2},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

thus the limit is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(Q7)
\series default
: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 be a bounded sequence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Prove that the sequence defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}=\sup\left\{ a_{k}:k\geq n\right\} $
\end_inset

 converges.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
We suppose directly that the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

 is bounded, then there exists a number 
\begin_inset Formula $M>0$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\abs{a_{n}}\leq M$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\N$
\end_inset

.
 According to the axiom of completeness, any upper bounded set has a least
 upper bound, in other words, a supremem.
 Thus the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup\left\{ a_{k}:k\geq n\right\} $
\end_inset

 exists for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k,n\in\N$
\end_inset

.
 The sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

 either converges or diverges.
 If it converges, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim\,y_{n}=\lim\,a_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

 does not converge, then the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ a_{k}:k\geq n\right\} $
\end_inset

 must have the same upper bound.
 ????
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\end_layout

